62. saginam caedite] This expression is very embarrassing. Let us first examine the meaning of the word sagina. In the writers upon rural affairs it signifies the act or process of fattening domestic animals.* Thus Varro R. R. III. 10 says that five points must be attended to in the management of geese—de genere, de fetura, de ovis, de pullis, de sagina, i. e. ‘the breed‚' ‘ the propagation,' ‘the eggs,’ ‘the goslings‚’ and ‘the process of fattening ;' and Columella VIII. 14 tells us that when the goslings are four months old the largest are to be selected and set aside sor fattening, farlurae maximus quisque destinatum· and then goes on, et est facilis harum avium sagina, i. e. ‘ the process of fattening these birds is easy;' so also Plin. H. N. IX. 56, ξ 82 informs us, on the authority of Varro, that Fulvius Lupinus, a short time before the civil war, was the first who kept snails in a preserve (coclearum vivaria instituit), and proceeds, quin el saginam earum commentus esl sapa el farre aliisque generibus, διο. In the above passages the word sagina denotes the ‘ art’ or ‘ process of fattening,’ and hence it easily passed into the signification found in Tacitus, Juvenal, δια, of the ‘materials used for fattening‚' ‘ nourishing, rich food,’ and hence ‘food' in general.
